It also seems like the people who didnâ€™t exercize may have been subjected to wording bias, maybe they felt bad for having not exercized. Exercise 3:

Recall: The correlation coefficient \(r\), is calculated using the below formula.

\[r = \dfrac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} z_x z_y = \dfrac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( \dfrac{x_i - \bar{x}}{s_x} \right) \left( \dfrac{y_i - \bar{y}}{s_y} \right)\] This value takes a very long time to compute by hand, especially when we have a lot of observations (i.e., a very large value for \(n\). It is more efficient to compute this value using a programming language like R.

Question 3: Type 1 and Type 2 errors

Null hypothesis: newspaper percentage is right Alternate hypothesis: newspaper percentage is false

Type 1 error: reject null hypothesis when null is true Type 1 Error: Called alpha Only depends on the value of alpha, and sample size doesnâ€™t matter

Type 2 error: reject alternate hypothesis when alternate is true Type 2 error: This is called beta, this error rate decreases as your sample size increases

Part a(i)

Yes, it is possible for either J or T to make a type 1 error. For J and T, this would mean rejecting the null hypothesis that the proportion of adults in their neighborhood who have graduated from high school is equal to 0.94 when that proportion is indeed true.

Both are equally likely to make a type 1 error since this error only depends on the value of $alpha and the sample size doesnâ€™t really matter in this case.

Part a(ii)

Yes, it is possible for either J or T to make a type 2 error. This means that J and T reject the alternative hypothesis that the proportion of adults in their neighborhood whoâ€™ve graduated from high school does not equal to 0.94, when the proportion truly isnâ€™t equal to 0.94.

J is more likely to make a type 2 error since his sample size of 200 is a lot smaller than Tâ€™s sample size of 500. This is because the error rate decreases as the sample size increases.

Null hypothesis: newspaper percentage is right

Alternate hypothesis: newspaper percentage is false

Type 1 error: reject null hypothesis when null is true

Type 1 Error: Called alpha Only depends on the value of alpha, and sample size doesnâ€™t matter

Type 2 error: reject alternate hypothesis when alternate is true

Type 2 error: This is called beta, this error rate decreases as your sample size increases

Part b(i)

It is not possible for either J or T to make a Type 1 error since we know that the null hypothesis that the newspaperâ€™s proportion of adults in their neighborhood who took chemistry of 0.25 is incorrect in the first place so even if we reject the null hypothesis, it isnâ€™t true to begin with to make that error.

Type 1 error is also dependent in $alpha and not sample size so since they both have the same alpha value, they have equal likelihood of commiting an error if it was possible. It isnâ€™t in this case.

Part b(ii)

Yes, it is possible for either J or T to make a type 2 error. This means that J and T reject the alternative hypothesis that the proportion of adults in their neighborhood whoâ€™ve taken high school chemostry from high school does not equal to 0.25, when the proportion truly isnâ€™t equal to 0.94.

J is more likely to make a type 2 error since his sample size of 200 is a lot smaller than Tâ€™s sample size of 500. This is because the error rate decreases as the sample size increases.
